\caption{Koide closure under eight natural scale prescriptions for the charm mass, with $m_b$ and $m_t$ held at their self-scales. Of the two lepton-derived scales in the perturbative regime, $m_\tau$ is the sharper of the two; of the quark-derived and conventional-reference scales, none produces closure within $10^{-3}$. The closure at $m_\tau$ is approximately $15\times$ tighter than the next-best alternative (lepton sum), $91\times$ tighter than the charm self-scale, $156\times$ tighter than the bottom self-scale, and $445\times$ tighter than the top self-scale.}
\label{tab:alt_scales}
\end{table}

Two structural features of this table deserve comment. First, both lepton-derived scales in the perturbative regime ($m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell$) produce tighter closures than any of the quark-derived or conventional-reference scales, by factors ranging from $6$ to $30$. This means the preference for lepton-derived scales is visible across both candidates, not just at the baseline. Second, within the lepton-derived candidates, $m_\tau$ is approximately an order of magnitude sharper than $\Sigma m_\ell$, and the two scales differ by only $106$~MeV in $\mu$. This sharpness within the lepton-scale family is unexplained by the present work and contributes to the open theoretical question of why $m_\tau$ specifically is preferred. We do not claim that $m_\tau$ is the unique possible natural scale; we claim that among the eight candidates tested, $m_\tau$ is empirically the sharpest, and that the preference is not a trivial consequence of the scan range or the choice of candidates.

\section{Statistical Characterization}
\label{sec:stats}

This section characterizes the observation under a set of frequentist test constructions, each with an explicitly defined null. Following the recommendation of Cousins \citep{CousinsMayoHEP2020}, the primary inferential object is the profile likelihood scan in the parameters of interest (Section~\ref{sec:confdist}), from which derived quantities such as $p$-values, confidence intervals, and severity statements can be read off. The remaining subsections (Sections~\ref{sec:plr}--\ref{sec:tiered}) report a series of constructions answering distinct null-conditional questions; we follow the interpretive register of the companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} in treating each as a model-conditional descriptive frequency under its specific construction, not as an unconditional significance claim. Section~\ref{sec:stats_register} addresses the relationship between the constructions and how they should and should not be combined.

\paragraph{Methodological note on post-discovery characterization.} The discrete scans reported in this section, particularly the heat-map scan of Section~\ref{sec:tiered}, were performed \textit{after} the (c,b,t) at $\mu = m_\tau$ observation was in hand, specifically for the purpose of characterizing the empirical null distribution of failures against which the observation can be evaluated. We note explicitly that this kind of post-discovery scan is methodologically distinct from a pre-discovery search: in a pre-discovery search, additional cells inflate the look-elsewhere correction against the searcher because each additional cell is a fresh chance to find a signal; in a post-discovery characterization scan, additional cells can only strengthen the observation (by revealing that other cells fail to produce comparable closures) or weaken it (by revealing that other cells \textit{do} produce comparable closures). Both outcomes are informative, and we report the full scan transparently regardless of which outcome it produced. The discipline followed throughout the post-discovery work was: state the hypothesis structure first, then run the analysis, then report whatever the analysis returned, without adjusting cell definitions or priors to make the observation look stronger or weaker than the data support.

\subsection{Profile likelihood scan: the primary inferential object}
\label{sec:confdist}

The complete inferential landscape in the parameters of interest is captured by the profile likelihood scan in $\Delta Q = Q|_{\mu = m_\tau} - 2/3$ and in the crossing scale $\mu^*$, with input quark masses and $\alpha_s$ profiled as nuisance parameters. We compute these scans on a fine grid and report $-2 \Delta \ln \mathcal{L}$ as a function of each parameter, from which the $1\sigma$ ($-2 \Delta \ln \mathcal{L} = 1$) and $2\sigma$ ($= 4$) intervals can be extracted directly.

For $\Delta Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$, scanned over the range $\Delta Q \in [-2 \times 10^{-3}, +2 \times 10^{-3}]$:
\begin{itemize}
\item Best-fit: $\Delta Q = +7.6 \times 10^{-5}$, with $-2 \Delta \ln \mathcal{L}_{\min} \approx 0.003$
\item 68\% CL interval: $\Delta Q \in [-4.2 \times 10^{-4}, \, +5.2 \times 10^{-4}]$
\item 95\% CL interval: $\Delta Q \in [-9.7 \times 10^{-4}, \, +1.1 \times 10^{-3}]$
\end{itemize}
The interval contains $\Delta Q = 0$ comfortably at $1\sigma$. The width of the $1\sigma$ interval ($\sim 10^{-3}$) is set by the propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q$ from Section~\ref{sec:error_budget}, with $m_t$ as the dominant nuisance parameter.

For the crossing scale $\mu^*$ (the value of $\mu$ at which $Q(c,b,t) = 2/3$ exactly), scanned over the perturbative range:
\begin{itemize}
\item Best-fit: $\mu^* = 1.7715$~GeV, with $-2 \Delta \ln \mathcal{L}_{\min} \approx 0.001$
\item 68\% CL interval: $\mu^* \in [1.704, \, 1.840]$~GeV
\item 95\% CL interval: $\mu^* \in [1.636, \, 1.933]$~GeV
\end{itemize}
The 68\% CL interval contains $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV; the 95\% CL interval contains both $m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.88303$~GeV. The data resolve $m_\tau$ from $\Sigma m_\ell$ at $1\sigma$ but not at $2\sigma$.

These two scans are the primary statistical objects of the paper. All subsequent constructions in this section are derived analyses of the same likelihood surface or characterizations under specific null constructions. We discourage readers from extracting a single ``$p$-value'' from the scans and treating it as a discovery threshold; the appropriate use of the scans is to read off the consistency of any specific value of $\Delta Q$ or $\mu^*$ at any chosen confidence level, in the manner of the LHC Higgs coupling measurements \citep{CousinsMayoHEP2020}.

\subsection{Profile likelihood ratio test}
\label{sec:plr}

We construct the likelihood $\mathcal{L}(m_c, m_b, m_t, \alpha_s) = \prod_i N(\text{measured}_i \mid \text{true}_i, \sigma_i)$ over the four input measurements, treating them as uncorrelated Gaussian nuisance parameters. Under the hypothesis $H_A$ that there exists a perturbative-regime scale $\mu^*$ at which $Q(c, b, t)|_{m_c \text{ at } \mu^*, m_b \text{ at self}, m_t \text{ at self}} = 2/3$ exactly, the inputs are constrained to a three-dimensional surface parameterized by $\mu^*$. The profile likelihood ratio is
\begin{equation}
-2 \ln \lambda \;=\; -2 \ln \frac{\sup_{H_A} \mathcal{L}}{\sup \mathcal{L}}
\end{equation}
with the unconstrained denominator trivially maximized at the measured central values.

The result: at the best-fit $\mu^*_{H_A} = 1.7707$~GeV, $-2 \ln \lambda = 2.24 \times 10^{-4}$. At the specific value $\mu^* = m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV, $-2 \ln \lambda = 8.6 \times 10^{-3}$. Wilks's theorem \citep{Wilks1938} would give a $p$-value of $0.99$ at the best fit and $0.93$ at $m_\tau$, both indicating that the data are entirely consistent with $H_A$.

\paragraph{Wilks's theorem fails for this problem at current input precision.} We verified the validity of the $\chi^2_1$ asymptotic distribution by Monte Carlo, generating $2 \times 10^3$ pseudo-experiments on the $H_A$ surface and comparing the empirical distribution of $-2 \ln \lambda$ to $\chi^2_1$ via the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test. The KS $p$-value is $< 10^{-3}$: the empirical distribution does not match $\chi^2_1$. The empirical 95\% quantile of $-2 \ln \lambda$ under $H_A$ is $\approx 0.045$, compared to the $\chi^2_1$ 95\% quantile of $3.84$, a discrepancy of approximately two orders of magnitude. This degeneracy reflects the fact that at current input precision, the four nuisance parameters have sufficient flexibility to satisfy the $Q = 2/3$ constraint at essentially zero cost in likelihood: the constraint and the data are not separable by a likelihood ratio test until input precision improves substantially. Using the empirical calibration instead of Wilks gives a $p$-value of $0.93$ at the best fit. We report this as a limitation of the PLR test specifically at current measurement precision, not as a general unfalsifiability of the hypothesis: the Feldman-Cousins interval (Section~\ref{sec:fc_crossing}) and the severity analysis (Section~\ref{sec:severity}) are non-degenerate and do constrain the hypothesis, and the tiered scan analysis (Section~\ref{sec:tiered}) provides an empirical model-free percentile against the noise floor. The PLR test is reported here for completeness and for the record, and it will become discriminating as $\sigma(m_t)$ improves at future colliders; it is not the appropriate test of the lepton-scale hypothesis at PDG 2024 precision, and the frequentist objects of inferential interest are the F-C interval, the severity result, and the tiered percentile.

\subsection{Null-model Monte Carlo over heavy-quark triples (Koide-conditioned null)}
\label{sec:null_mc}

We port the null-model architecture from the companion note's Section~5.4 to the heavy quark case. Synthetic heavy-quark-like triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ are sampled with $m_3$ log-uniform in $[10, 500]$~GeV, $m_1/m_3$ log-uniform in $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}]$, and $m_2$ solved from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$ to produce a Koide-saturated triple. To each valid triple we apply the discovery rule: hold $m_2$ and $m_3$ at their sampled self-scales, evaluate the rescaled-charm Koide $Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$, and ask whether $|Q - 2/3| < $ threshold. We accumulate $10^5$ valid triples after filtering and repeat under four priors: a baseline (Prior~A), two sensitivity variants (B, C), and one deliberately adversarial linear-uniform sampling (D). Hit fractions with 95\% Clopper-Pearson confidence intervals at the observed-residual threshold ($5 \times 10^{-5}$) are:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prior & Hit fraction at $|Q-2/3| < 5 \times 10^{-5}$ & Observed-percentile rank \\
\midrule
A (baseline log-uniform) & $0.43\%$ \, $[0.39, 0.47]$ & 0.4 \\
B (wider $m_3$ range) & $0.40\%$ \, $[0.37, 0.45]$ & 0.4 \\
C (wider hierarchy) & $0.42\%$ \, $[0.38, 0.47]$ & 0.4 \\
D (adversarial linear-uniform) & $0.29\%$ \, $[0.25, 0.32]$ & 0.3 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Null-model Monte Carlo hit fractions for the heavy Koide observation under four priors over heavy-quark-like Koide-saturated triples. The observed (c,b,t) residual sits at the $\sim 0.4$ percentile of the null distribution under all priors. The adversarial linear-uniform prior reduces the hit fraction relative to the baseline, which is the correct behavior. The hit fraction is robust across the reasonable prior range tested.}
\label{tab:null_mc}
\end{table}

This characterization is conditional on the prior over heavy-quark-like triples and on the Koide-saturation conditioning. It is not an unconditional $p$-value against a physical null; it is the frequency with which the discovery rule produces a comparable closure under the specified Monte Carlo construction. The companion note used a similar construction (lepton triples, Koide-saturated) and reported $\sim 0.5\%$ hit fractions under analogous priors. The present result is at the same order of magnitude, indicating that the present observation matches the companion note's statistical bar under the same construction.

\subsection{Parametric bootstrap and look-elsewhere correction}
\label{sec:bootstrap}

The Koide-conditioned Monte Carlo of Section~\ref{sec:null_mc} answers ``how rare is a tight closure among random Koide-saturated heavy triples?''~The complementary question --- ``given the observed input quark masses with their measurement uncertainties, how often would noise alone produce a tight closure near \textit{some} natural scale?'' --- is answered by a parametric bootstrap following the Gross-Vitells approach \citep{GrossVitells2010}. We draw $10^4$ pseudo-experiments from the input measurement uncertainties around the observed central values, run the full analysis on each (computing $Q(\mu)$ across the perturbative scan range, finding the minimum $|Q - 2/3|$ and its location), and count hits by two definitions:
\begin{itemize}
\item Local hit: minimum $|Q - 2/3|$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ specifically is tighter than the observed $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$.
\item Global hit: minimum $|Q - 2/3|$ anywhere in the scan is tighter than observed \textit{and} the scale at which the minimum occurs falls within $\sim 73$~MeV (the input-uncertainty-equivalent width) of one of the six natural scale candidates from Table~\ref{tab:alt_scales}.
\end{itemize}

The result:
\begin{itemize}
\item Local $p$-value: $0.072 \, [0.067, 0.077]$
\item Global $p$-value (look-elsewhere over the six natural scales): $0.417 \, [0.407, 0.426]$
\item Effective trials factor: $5.8$
\end{itemize}

This is the harder of the two null constructions. Under the parametric bootstrap, approximately $42\%$ of pseudo-experiments drawn from current input uncertainties produce a closure as tight as the observed one near \textit{some} natural scale, after correction for the freedom to choose which natural scale to test. The local $p$-value at $m_\tau$ specifically is $\approx 7\%$. We report both: the bootstrap is the appropriate null when the question is ``could this happen by input noise hunting?''~and the answer is, at current precision, ``yes, about half the time at any scale, or about one time in fifteen at $m_\tau$ specifically.''

The contrast between Sections~\ref{sec:null_mc} and \ref{sec:bootstrap} is structural and intentional: the Koide-conditioned null treats the triple as already living on the Koide surface and asks how rare it is for a tight closure to land at $m_\tau$, while the parametric bootstrap treats the triple as fixed at its observed values and asks how rare it is for noise to produce a tight closure anywhere natural. They condition on different things and they answer different questions; combining them into a single $p$-value would conflate the conditioning and is methodologically incorrect (see Section~\ref{sec:stats_register}).

\subsection{Feldman-Cousins confidence interval on the crossing scale}
\label{sec:fc_crossing}

The estimated zero-crossing scale $\hat{\mu}^* = 1.76952$~GeV is a point estimate of a parameter physically bounded to the perturbative regime. We construct the 68\% and 95\% CL intervals on the true crossing scale using the unified approach of Feldman and Cousins \citep{FeldmanCousins1998}, which handles bounded parameters without ad-hoc upper/lower-limit switching. For each hypothesized $\mu_{\text{true}}$ on a grid in $[1.4, 2.2]$~GeV, the empirical distribution of $\hat{\mu}^*$ under pseudo-experiments on the $Q = 2/3$ constraint surface at $\mu_{\text{true}}$ is computed; the likelihood-ratio ordering defines acceptance regions; the confidence belt is inverted at the observed $\hat{\mu}^* = 1.76952$~GeV.

The result:
\begin{itemize}
\item 68\% CL interval: $\mu^* \in [1.698, \, 1.847]$~GeV \quad ($m_\tau \in $ interval; $\Sigma m_\ell$ \textit{not} in interval)
\item 95\% CL interval: $\mu^* \in [1.631, \, 1.915]$~GeV \quad ($m_\tau \in $ interval; $\Sigma m_\ell \in $ interval)
\end{itemize}

The interpretation is precise. At $1\sigma$, the data resolve $m_\tau$ from $\Sigma m_\ell$ as the crossing scale: $m_\tau$ sits inside the 68\% CL interval, $\Sigma m_\ell$ does not. At $2\sigma$, the data do not resolve them: both are in the 95\% CL interval. The improvement in resolution between $1\sigma$ and $2\sigma$ is what would be gained by future precision improvements in $m_t$ (Section~\ref{sec:severity}).

\subsection{Severity at current and projected precision}
\label{sec:severity}

Following the error-statistical framework of Mayo and Spanos \citep{MayoSpanos2006}, the severity with which the data warrant the claim ``$\mu^*_{\text{crossing}} = m_\tau$'' is quantified by the power of the test to reject that claim against alternatives. For a grid of alternative hypotheses $\mu_{\text{alt}}$ in $[1.5, 2.0]$~GeV, we generate pseudo-experiments assuming $\mu^*_{\text{true}} = \mu_{\text{alt}}$, run the analysis on each, and compute the fraction that would reject ``$\mu^* = m_\tau$'' at 95\% CL.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Precision regime & $\sigma(\hat{\mu}^*)$ (MeV) & 50\% power distance from $m_\tau$ (MeV) & Power at $\Sigma m_\ell$ \\
\midrule
Current (PDG/FLAG 2024) & $77.9$ & $169$ & $31.7\%$ \\
Projected (factor-5 $\sigma(m_t)$ improvement) & $38.6$ & $92$ & $81.1\%$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Severity / power analysis for the claim $\mu^*_{\text{crossing}} = m_\tau$ at current and projected input precision. ``50\% power distance'' is the alternative hypothesis $\mu_{\text{alt}}$ at which the test rejects $\mu^* = m_\tau$ in 50\% of pseudo-experiments. ``Power at $\Sigma m_\ell$'' is the power against the specific alternative $\mu_{\text{alt}} = \Sigma m_\ell = 1.883$~GeV (the companion-note scale). The factor-5 reduction in $\sigma(m_t)$ corresponds approximately to the HL-LHC scenario; full $e^+e^-$ projected precision is roughly a factor of 14.}
\label{tab:severity}
\end{table}

The severity result is the most consequential numerical finding in this section. At current precision, the data have only $32\%$ power to reject $\mu^* = m_\tau$ in favor of $\mu^* = \Sigma m_\ell$: the two scales are not empirically distinguishable. At projected factor-5 precision on $m_t$, the power increases to $81\%$, and $m_\tau$ becomes empirically distinguishable from $\Sigma m_\ell$ at high confidence. \textit{This is the test the lepton-scale hypothesis will face in the next round of measurement updates.} The hypothesis predicts that as $\sigma(m_t)$ improves, the central value of the residual at $\mu = m_\tau$ will remain within the shrinking $\sigma_Q$ band; if the residual moves outside the band as inputs tighten, the hypothesis is excluded at the corresponding confidence level. The pre-registration of this prediction is documented in Section~\ref{sec:predictions}.

\paragraph{Visibility as a precision-era result.} The visibility of the closure relative to $\sigma_Q$ is itself a precision-era artifact in a substantive sense: under PDG 2010 uncertainties on $m_t$ (when $\sigma(m_t) \approx 1.4$~GeV, twice the current value), $\sigma_Q$ would have been approximately $1.0 \times 10^{-3}$ rather than the current $5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, and the residual-to-$\sigma$ ratio would have been at the $0.05$ level rather than the current $0.10$. The same observation, with the same algebra and the same scale prescription, would not have been visible as a structurally tight closure under input precision available a decade earlier. The result is therefore enabled by the precision of $m_t$ available in PDG 2024, and the same logic that makes future precision improvements informative (Prediction 1) also means that the closure's current visibility at $\sim 0.1\sigma$ is contingent on having precise measurements of all three input masses today.

\subsection{Discrete hypothesis scan and tiered analysis}
\label{sec:tiered}

The most stringent characterization of the observation is a discrete scan over the full enumerable hypothesis space defined by the construction in Section~\ref{sec:bounds}. Following a methodological recommendation grounded in the Higgs-search look-elsewhere framework \citep{GrossVitells2010,CousinsMayoHEP2020}, we performed a complete enumeration over four axes: (i) triple, with five candidates including same-generation sequential heavy and light triples and two mixed-generation alternatives; (ii) target fraction $p/q$ with $p, q$ positive integers, $q \leq 10$, restricted to the physically relevant range; (iii) evaluation scale, with fourteen candidates including all physical particle masses through the Higgs and several round-number reference scales (1, 1.5, 2, 3 GeV) included to populate the empirical noise floor; and (iv) sign pattern, with all four distinct sign assignments on the square roots after quotienting by the global sign-flip invariance of $Q$. The total grid contains $N = 10{,}640$ cells.

For each cell, we compute the approximate $\chi^2$ as $((Q_{\text{cell}} - Q_{\text{target}})/\sigma_Q)^2$ where $\sigma_Q$ is the propagated input uncertainty appropriate to that triple. Below-perturbative cells are flagged and excluded from the noise-floor analysis. Top cells are re-evaluated with the full profile-likelihood treatment for sharper numbers.

\paragraph{Tiered partition.} Following Cousins's principle that the look-elsewhere correction must reflect the trial structure that was actually employed, we partition the $N = 10{,}640$ cells into two tiers defined by the lepton-scale hypothesis as stated in the companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} \textit{prior to any heat-map computation}:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Tier~1}: cells for which the triple is $(c, b, t)$, the target is $Q = 2/3$ (Koide 1981), the scale is one of the two lepton-derived candidates ($m_\tau$ or $\Sigma m_\ell$), and the sign pattern is the standard Koide $(+,+,+)$. This is exactly two cells: \textbf{T1a} $= (c,b,t)$ at $(2/3, m_\tau)$ and \textbf{T1b} $= (c,b,t)$ at $(2/3, \Sigma m_\ell)$.
\item \textbf{Tier~2}: all $N_2 = 10{,}638$ remaining cells. These serve as the empirical noise floor and as a source of potential post-hoc discoveries for future investigation.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textit{Bright-line statement.} The tier partition was defined by the lepton-scale hypothesis from the companion note before the heat map computation; the assignment of cells to tiers does not depend on $\chi^2$ values or any other scan result. Tier~1 would have contained the same two cells regardless of where they ranked in the final $\chi^2$ ordering.

\paragraph{Tier~1 results.} The two pre-stated cells:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{T1a}: $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \, \mu = m_\tau, \, (+,+,+))$. $\chi^2 = 0.010$. The headline cell of the present paper. Empirical percentile against the Tier~2 noise floor: $0.011$th (1 of $9{,}118$ cells, Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI $[0.0003\%, 0.061\%]$).
\item \textbf{T1b}: $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \, \mu = \Sigma m_\ell, \, (+,+,+))$. $\chi^2 = 2.15$. The other lepton-derived candidate from the discovery chronology. Empirical percentile against Tier~2: $0.16\%$ (15 of $9{,}118$ cells, 95\% CI $[0.092\%, 0.27\%]$). Rank 6 of the $2{,}280$ Tier~2 cells in the standard $(+,+,+)$ panel.
\end{itemize}
T1a is the closer fit; T1b is at the $\sim 1.5\sigma$ level. Both pre-stated cells sit in the upper tail of the empirical distribution. T1b is reported alongside T1a as a transparency element: the lepton-scale hypothesis tested two scales, only one produced a tight closure, and we report both outcomes as part of the pre-registered test.

The empirical percentile reported for T1a is the model-free frequency at which Tier~2 cells achieve $\chi^2$ as low as the pre-stated cell. We use the term \emph{percentile} rather than \emph{$p$-value} to make explicit that it is not the probability that the observation arises by chance under a generative model for the quark masses --- the Tier~2 distribution is not a generative model, it is the combinatorial noise floor of the discrete scan computed on the same measured masses. The percentile answers the question ``how unusual is the predicted cell's closure compared to the noise floor of the discrete scan?'' and not the question ``what is the probability that this observation arises by chance?''

\paragraph{Note on the Clopper-Pearson interval and cell correlations.} The Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI reported above treats the $9{,}118$ Tier~2 cells as independent binomial trials, which they strictly are not: $Q(\text{triple})(\mu)$ is a smooth function of $\mu$, and neighboring (target, scale) cells within the same triple and sign convention share most of their structural content. The effective sample size is therefore smaller than $9{,}118$ by a factor that we estimate but do not compute exactly here, conservatively bounded by the number of distinct (triple, sign) combinations ($5 \times 4 = 20$) times the number of independent scale clusters in the perturbative range (approximately $3$ when one accounts for the smooth $Q(\mu)$ correlation length), giving an effective sample size of $\sim 60$. The corrected Clopper-Pearson CI under that effective sample size is wider than the one reported, but the qualitative conclusion --- that T1a is at the lowest empirical $\chi^2$ percentile of the Tier~2 distribution and that no other cell in the scan with standard $(+,+,+)$ Koide signs survives fine-grid verification --- is robust to the correlation correction. A block-bootstrap correction that respects the smooth-curve structure within each (triple, sign) panel is left to future work.

\paragraph{Tier~2 noise-floor characterization.} The empirical CDF of $\chi^2$ across the $N_2 = 9{,}118$ Tier~2 cells (excluding $1{,}520$ below-perturbative sentinel cells) defines the noise-floor distribution. Of these cells:
\begin{itemize}
\item $8$ cells have $\chi^2 < 1$
\item $22$ cells have $\chi^2 < 4$
\item $39$ cells have $\chi^2 < 9$
\end{itemize}

