\paragraph{Recovery of Rivero's $(s,c,b)$ observation.} Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} reported in 2011 that the $(s,c,b)$ triple with the $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention closes the Koide relation to approximately $2\%$. The present scan recovers this observation as a $(-,+,+)$ sign-convention cell at rank $19$ with $\chi^2 = 2.32$ (a $\sim 1.5\sigma$ near-miss for $Q = 2/3$ at $3$~GeV), confirming the stability of Rivero's observation under updated FLAG/PDG inputs and four-loop running but not constituting an independent test --- the algebra and the input masses are the same as in Rivero's calculation; only the precision of the inputs has been refined. The recovery serves as a cross-check on the scan infrastructure: a known observation in the literature is rediscovered at approximately the expected location and significance, confirming that the scan is doing its job correctly. It is not a Tier~1 cell under the present paper's hypothesis (the sign convention differs and the $(s,c,b)$ triple was not pre-stated), and we do not claim it as a second hit. We report it because it is a published observation that the scan independently rediscovers.

