\title{A Koide Relation for the (c, b, t) Quark Triple at \texorpdfstring{$\mu = m_\tau$}{mu = m\_tau}}
\author{Andrew M. Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 14, 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2 = 2/3$ holds for the charged leptons to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} and has since been examined as a candidate structural relation in the quark sector \citep{Rivero2011}. In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported a related observation: the outer Soddy curvature of the Koide lepton triple matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. Here we test the same underlying hypothesis---that lepton-derived renormalization scales enter the characterization of quark-sector Koide-type relations---on an independent target, the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$. Using uniform $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses with $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$, and $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ via four-loop QCD running, we find $Q(c, b, t) = 0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, against a propagated input-uncertainty budget $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ dominated by $m_t$.

The primary inferential object of the paper is the profile likelihood scan in $\Delta Q = Q|_{\mu = m_\tau} - 2/3$ and in the crossing scale $\mu^*$ at which $Q(c, b, t) = 2/3$ exactly. The scan in $\Delta Q$ is consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$, with 68\% CL interval $[-4.2, +5.2] \times 10^{-4}$. The scan in $\mu^*$ has best fit $1.7715$~GeV; the 68\% CL interval $[1.704, 1.840]$~GeV contains $m_\tau$, and the 95\% CL interval $[1.636, 1.933]$~GeV contains both $m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.883$~GeV. The data resolve $m_\tau$ from $\Sigma m_\ell$ at $1\sigma$ but not at $2\sigma$. A discrete enumeration over $N = 10{,}640$ cells in the (triple, target, scale, sign) hypothesis space, partitioned into a Tier~1 (cells pre-stated by the lepton-scale hypothesis) and a Tier~2 (the empirical noise floor), finds the predicted Tier~1 cell $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \mu = m_\tau, (+,+,+))$ at $\chi^2 = 0.010$. The cell ranks at the $0.011$th percentile of the Tier~2 noise floor (1 of 9{,}118 cells, Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI $[3 \times 10^{-6}, 6.1 \times 10^{-4}]$). After fine-grid verification at the hypothesis-stated scale applied uniformly to all eight sub-$\chi^2 = 1$ cells across all four sign panels, the predicted cell is the unique cell in the entire $10{,}640$-cell scan whose $\chi^2$ is irreducible at a hypothesis-stated or named scale; every other sub-$1$ cell, regardless of sign convention, is verified as a discretization artifact with $\chi^2$ reduction factor $\leq 0.014$ under fine-grid resampling at the actual zero crossing. The $(s,c,b)$ triple with the Rivero $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention appears in the same scan as a $\sim 1.5\sigma$ warm spot at $Q = 2/3$ at $3$~GeV ($\chi^2 = 2.32$); the scan recovers Rivero's 2011 observation under updated FLAG/PDG inputs and four-loop running, providing a cross-check on the scan infrastructure but not constituting an independent test. Both the three-loop and four-loop residuals are within $\sigma_Q$ of exact closure; the loop-order progression is monotone in sign and the all-orders asymptote is not yet determined.

A pre-registered falsifiability prediction states that under projected factor-5 improvement in $\sigma(m_t)$, the empirical power to distinguish $\mu = m_\tau$ from $\mu = \Sigma m_\ell$ as the crossing scale increases from $32\%$ to $81\%$, providing the principal opportunity to falsify the lepton-scale assignment. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or broader structural implication; the preference for $\mu = m_\tau$ is flagged as the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; heavy quark masses; charm mass; $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running; four-loop QCD; Standard Model mass sector; lepton-derived scales; severity testing; look-elsewhere effect
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The Koide relation \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \equiv \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} = \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide_lepton}
\end{equation}
holds for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$ and has been the subject of continuous theoretical investigation for over four decades without an accepted derivation. Extensions to the quark sector have been attempted repeatedly. Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to approximately $2\%$ and developed the chained-Koide ``waterfall'' construction. Symmetry-based approaches have been pursued by Sumino \citep{Sumino2009} via family gauge symmetry, and extensions to the neutrino sector have been discussed by Brannen \citep{Brannen2006} and others \citep{RodejohannZhang2011,Krolikowski2014}. We treat \eqref{eq:koide_lepton} as an empirical input throughout this paper.

In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026}, we examined the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F} \equiv k_4^-$ of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton Descartes configuration and reported that $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV is numerically consistent with the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau = 1883.0$~MeV within current FLAG lattice precision (residual $+0.042$~MeV against a dominant lattice uncertainty of $\pm 0.69$~MeV). That observation concerned a lepton-derived quantity matching a quark mass at a lepton-derived scale, and was accompanied by a Koide-conditioned null-model characterization over lepton mass triples.

\paragraph{The hypothesis tested here.} The present paper tests the same underlying hypothesis on an independent target. The hypothesis, stated minimally, is: \textit{lepton-derived renormalization scales enter the characterization of quark-sector Koide-type relations}. The companion note tested this on the strange-quark mass via a lepton-Descartes geometric construction. Here we test it on the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ via the Koide relation itself, evaluated at a candidate lepton-derived scale. The algebraic construction (Koide's $Q$) is unchanged from Koide 1981. The geometric reading is that of Kocik 2012 \citep{Kocik2012}, also unchanged. The only structural element being tested is whether the lepton-derived scale choice that worked in the companion note, or a neighboring one, also produces a tight closure on an independent target.

\paragraph{Minimality of the construction.} Stated as a single sentence: the only construction-level change introduced relative to the standard Koide setup is that the renormalization scale at which one element of the triple is evaluated may be drawn from the charged-lepton pole-mass spectrum, rather than being restricted to the quark sector. The functional form (Koide's $Q$), the target value ($2/3$), the triple structure (three same-sector quarks), the renormalization scheme ($\overline{\mathrm{MS}}$ throughout), and the sign convention (all positive square roots) are all unchanged. Within the $(c, b, t)$ triple, the choice of which mass to run is not a free degree of freedom: $m_c$ is the unique mass whose self-scale ($1.28$~GeV) lies below $m_\tau$ ($1.78$~GeV) in the perturbative regime. Running $m_c$ upward from $m_c(m_c)$ to $\mu = m_\tau$ is small and well-defined --- a single-flavor region with no threshold crossings and a fractional shift of $-10.78\%$. Running $m_b$ instead would require running $m_b$ \textit{downward} from $m_b(m_b) = 4.20$~GeV to $m_\tau$, crossing the bottom threshold in the wrong direction, with a fractional shift of $+22.58\%$. Running $m_t$ would similarly require running downward from $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV through both bottom and charm thresholds, with a fractional shift of $+87.44\%$. The shifts for $m_b$ and $m_t$ are orders of magnitude larger than the input-uncertainty budget $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ that controls whether the closure is visible at all. The hypothesis therefore specifies a single mass to be varied (the charm evaluation scale) and a small finite set of candidate values (charged-lepton pole masses and their sums in the perturbative regime), and the choice of which mass to vary is uniquely determined by the physics of the $(c, b, t)$ triple, not by tuning. We note for explicitness that the lepton-scale admissibility is the only addition; the choice of charged-lepton (rather than neutrino) scales, of pole-mass sums (rather than products, ratios, or differences), of the $(c,b,t)$ triple specifically (the only same-generation sequential heavy triple containing a single mass below the lepton-scale window), and of the standard Koide $(+,+,+)$ sign convention, are all constraints inherited from prior literature \citep{Koide1982,Kocik2012,Rivero2011}, not new degrees of freedom introduced by the present work. The companion note tested an instance of this hypothesis on the strange-quark mass at $\mu_\star = \Sigma m_\ell$ via a lepton-Descartes geometric construction; the present paper tests it on the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ via the Koide relation directly. Whether the two instances are connected by a deeper structural mechanism, or are coincidental near-misses on the same minimal hypothesis, is not something we attempt to resolve here.

The result: the Koide relation $Q(c, b, t) = 2/3$ holds to a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ when $m_c$ is evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ via four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running, with $m_b$ and $m_t$ each held at their canonical self-scales. Propagating input-mass uncertainties through the running gives a total measurement-precision budget on $Q$ of $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, so the observed residual is approximately an order of magnitude smaller than the current propagated-input uncertainty on $Q$. This is a measurement-precision statement: given current input uncertainties, the observed $Q$ is indistinguishable from any value within a band of width $\sim \sigma_Q$ around $2/3$, including exact $2/3$. It is \textit{not} a frequentist significance statement; that characterization requires explicitly defined null models and is carried out in Section~\ref{sec:stats}. The dominant uncertainty source in the measurement-precision budget is the PDG value of $m_t$, not $m_c$ (despite $m_c$ being the only mass whose scale is being varied). Of seven natural lepton- and quark-derived scales tested in the perturbative regime, $m_\tau$ is approximately an order of magnitude tighter than the next-best alternative ($\Sigma m_\ell$, residual $7.5 \times 10^{-4}$) and two to three orders of magnitude tighter than the quark self-scales.

\paragraph{What this paper claims and does not claim.} We claim that a specific numerical observation exists, that it is stable under the input uncertainties currently available, and that it is not trivially reproduced by neighboring scale choices. We do not derive the relation. We do not propose a mechanism. In particular, we do not derive why $\mu = m_\tau$ should be the preferred scale; the scan result at neighboring candidate scales is an empirical characterization, not an explanation. The question of why $m_\tau$ specifically is the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation and we make no attempt to answer it here.

The organization is as follows. Section~\ref{sec:setup} fixes notation, the scheme, and the input values. Section~\ref{sec:observation} reports the closure at $\mu = m_\tau$, the full measurement-precision decomposition, and the continuous scale dependence. Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales} reports the discrete scale-prescription scan over natural alternatives. Section~\ref{sec:stats} provides the full frequentist statistical characterization, structured around the profile likelihood scan as the primary inferential object (Section~\ref{sec:confdist}), with complementary analyses including a profile likelihood ratio test (Section~\ref{sec:plr}), a Koide-conditioned null-model Monte Carlo (Section~\ref{sec:null_mc}), a parametric bootstrap with look-elsewhere correction (Section~\ref{sec:bootstrap}), a Feldman-Cousins confidence interval on the crossing scale (Section~\ref{sec:fc_crossing}), severity curves at current and projected future precision (Section~\ref{sec:severity}), and a tiered discrete enumeration of the full hypothesis space partitioning the $N = 10{,}640$ scan cells into pre-stated (Tier~1) and scan-found (Tier~2) cells with empirical noise floor characterization (Section~\ref{sec:tiered}). Section~\ref{sec:bounds} makes explicit the structural bounds on the search space within which the observation was found. Section~\ref{sec:chronology} discloses the order of operations and the prior-knowledge bounds on the author's search. Section~\ref{sec:caveats} makes the non-claims explicit. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses the relation to the companion note and to Rivero's construction, reports pre-registered falsifiability predictions, and concludes.

\section{Setup and Notation}
\label{sec:setup}

We work in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme throughout for the quark masses. Input central values and their uncertainties:

\begin{itemize}
\item $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$ \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV (FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$ \citep{FLAG2024})
\item $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV ($\overline{\text{MS}}$, derived from PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024})
\item $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ \citep{PDG2024}
\item $m_e = 0.5109989461$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6583755$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV \citep{PDG2024}
\end{itemize}

All three heavy quark masses are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quantities evaluated at their canonical self-scales. We emphasize this explicitly because the Koide combination at $10^{-5}$ precision is sensitive to scheme: mixing $\overline{\text{MS}}$ with pole masses in the same triple would introduce shifts of order $(10-20)\%$ on $m_t$ alone, orders of magnitude larger than the observed residual, and would constitute a different and physically inconsistent quantity. The single structural element the paper varies is the evaluation scale of $m_c$, not its scheme.

Running between scales is performed via four-loop QCD using \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec}, with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and full threshold matching at $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$, giving active-flavor regions $n_f \in \{3, 4, 5, 6\}$. For each evaluation of $m_c$ at a scale $\mu \neq m_c(m_c)$, $m_c$ is run from its self-scale to $\mu$ under the appropriate $n_f$ region. The Koide combination is then evaluated as
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)(\mu) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_c(\mu) + m_b(m_b) + m_t(m_t)}{\left(\sqrt{m_c(\mu)} + \sqrt{m_b(m_b)} + \sqrt{m_t(m_t)}\right)^2},
\label{eq:Q_def}
\end{equation}
where only $m_c$ carries a $\mu$-dependence. In this prescription the Koide relation is not an RG-invariant: its residual depends on the charm evaluation scale. This is a feature of the test, not an accident; the purpose of the scale scan is precisely to locate the scale at which the residual is smallest.

\section{The Observation}
\label{sec:observation}

At the central input values and $\mu = m_\tau$:
\begin{equation}
m_c(m_\tau) = 1.14262~\text{GeV}, \qquad Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 0.666717692.
\label{eq:headline}
\end{equation}
The residual against $2/3$ is
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} - \frac{2}{3} \;=\; +5.10 \times 10^{-5}.
\label{eq:residual}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Input Uncertainty Decomposition}
\label{sec:error_budget}

We propagate each input uncertainty independently through the four-loop running and Koide combination to obtain the contribution of each source to $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$. Table~\ref{tab:budget} shows the decomposition.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution to $Q$ & Fraction of total variance \\
\midrule
FLAG $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807 \pm 0.0013$~GeV & $4.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & 0.65\% \\
FLAG $m_b(m_b) = 4.203 \pm 0.011$~GeV & $1.82 \times 10^{-4}$ & 12.8\% \\
PDG $m_t(m_t) = 162.5 \pm 0.7$~GeV & $4.73 \times 10^{-4}$ & 86.4\% \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $1.78 \times 10^{-4}$ & (separate) \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs.\ 3L) & $2.87 \times 10^{-5}$ & $<$1\% \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum (quark masses only) & $5.09 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
Quadrature sum (including $\alpha_s$) & $5.39 \times 10^{-4}$ & \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Decomposition of $\sigma_Q$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ under independent variation of each input. The PDG uncertainty on $m_t$ dominates the budget by roughly a factor of 2.6 over the next-largest contribution, the $\alpha_s(M_Z)$ running-coupling uncertainty. The FLAG uncertainty on $m_c(m_c)$---the only mass whose scale is being varied in the test---contributes less than 1\% of the total variance. The four-loop truncation uncertainty, estimated as the 4L-3L shift, is at the $10^{-5}$ level and comparable to the observed residual.}
\label{tab:budget}
\end{table}

Combining the quark-mass contributions and $\alpha_s$ in quadrature gives a total input-propagation uncertainty of $\sigma_Q \approx 5.39 \times 10^{-4}$. The observed residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ is approximately a factor of ten smaller than this. This ratio is a \textit{measurement-precision} statement: the current uncertainty on $Q$ given published input masses and $\alpha_s$ is approximately ten times larger than the observed deviation from $2/3$, meaning that at current input precision the observed $Q$ value cannot be empirically distinguished from any value within a band of width $\sim \sigma_Q$ centered on $2/3$ (of which exact $2/3$ is one particular value, but so is $2/3 + 3 \times 10^{-4}$ and many others). This is not a statistical significance claim and should not be read as one; a frequentist characterization of how unusual this closure is requires a defined null distribution, which we construct in Section~\ref{sec:stats}.

