\subsection{Continuous Scale Sensitivity}
\label{sec:continuous}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)(\mu)$ as a continuous function of the charm evaluation scale across $\mu \in [1.0, 10000]$~GeV using the precomputed running-mass lookup table (1022 scale points, logarithmically spaced). The full curve is monotonic on each side of a minimum located near $\mu = m_\tau$. The exact zero-crossing of $(Q - 2/3)$ on the interpolation grid occurs at
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star^{\text{crossing}} \;=\; 1.76952~\text{GeV},
\label{eq:crossing}
\end{equation}
which is 7.3~MeV below $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV. Since $dQ/d\mu \approx 6.94 \times 10^{-3}~\text{GeV}^{-1}$ near the crossing, the shift in $Q$ induced by a $\sigma_Q$ shift in inputs corresponds to a $\mu$ shift of approximately $73$~MeV. The observed 7.3~MeV offset of the crossing from $m_\tau$ is therefore approximately a factor of ten smaller than this input-propagated width on the crossing scale: at current input precision, $m_\tau$ and the crossing scale cannot be empirically distinguished. This is the same type of measurement-precision statement made for the residual above, expressed on the $\mu$ axis rather than the $Q$ axis, and is subject to the same interpretive caveat: the frequentist confidence interval on the crossing scale is computed via the Feldman-Cousins unified approach \citep{FeldmanCousins1998} in Section~\ref{sec:stats}.

The width of the $\mu$-window around $m_\tau$ within which $|Q - 2/3|$ stays below various thresholds is:
\begin{itemize}
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.76, 1.78]$~GeV, width $\approx 20$~MeV (1.1\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 3 \times 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.73, 1.81]$~GeV, width $\approx 80$~MeV (4.5\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 5.1 \times 10^{-4} \approx \sigma_Q$: $\mu \in [1.70, 1.84]$~GeV, width $\approx 140$~MeV (7.9\% of $m_\tau$)
\end{itemize}
The $\sigma_Q$-equivalent window is narrow in $\mu$: the closure is sharp on the continuous scale axis, not a broad flat minimum that happens to contain $m_\tau$.

