\begin{abstract}
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2 = 2/3$ holds for the charged leptons to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} and has since been examined as a candidate structural relation in the quark sector \citep{Rivero2011}. In a companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} we reported a related observation: the outer Soddy curvature of the Koide lepton triple matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. Here we test the same underlying hypothesis---that lepton-derived renormalization scales enter the characterization of quark-sector Koide-type relations---on an independent target, the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$. Using uniform $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses with $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t$ at $m_t(m_t)$, and $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ via four-loop QCD running, we find $Q(c, b, t) = 0.666718$ against $2/3 = 0.666667$, a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, against a propagated input-uncertainty budget $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ dominated by $m_t$.

The primary inferential object of the paper is the profile likelihood scan in $\Delta Q = Q|_{\mu = m_\tau} - 2/3$ and in the crossing scale $\mu^*$ at which $Q(c, b, t) = 2/3$ exactly. The scan in $\Delta Q$ is consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$, with 68\% CL interval $[-4.2, +5.2] \times 10^{-4}$. The scan in $\mu^*$ has best fit $1.7715$~GeV; the 68\% CL interval $[1.704, 1.840]$~GeV contains $m_\tau$, and the 95\% CL interval $[1.636, 1.933]$~GeV contains both $m_\tau$ and $\Sigma m_\ell = 1.883$~GeV. The data resolve $m_\tau$ from $\Sigma m_\ell$ at $1\sigma$ but not at $2\sigma$. A discrete enumeration over $N = 10{,}640$ cells in the (triple, target, scale, sign) hypothesis space, partitioned into a Tier~1 (cells pre-stated by the lepton-scale hypothesis) and a Tier~2 (the empirical noise floor), finds the predicted Tier~1 cell $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \mu = m_\tau, (+,+,+))$ at $\chi^2 = 0.010$. The cell ranks at the $0.011$th percentile of the Tier~2 noise floor (1 of 9{,}118 cells, Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI $[3 \times 10^{-6}, 6.1 \times 10^{-4}]$). After fine-grid verification at the hypothesis-stated scale applied uniformly to all eight sub-$\chi^2 = 1$ cells across all four sign panels, the predicted cell is the unique cell in the entire $10{,}640$-cell scan whose $\chi^2$ is irreducible at a hypothesis-stated or named scale; every other sub-$1$ cell, regardless of sign convention, is verified as a discretization artifact with $\chi^2$ reduction factor $\leq 0.014$ under fine-grid resampling at the actual zero crossing. The $(s,c,b)$ triple with the Rivero $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention appears in the same scan as a $\sim 1.5\sigma$ warm spot at $Q = 2/3$ at $3$~GeV ($\chi^2 = 2.32$); the scan recovers Rivero's 2011 observation under updated FLAG/PDG inputs and four-loop running, providing a cross-check on the scan infrastructure but not constituting an independent test. Both the three-loop and four-loop residuals are within $\sigma_Q$ of exact closure; the loop-order progression is monotone in sign and the all-orders asymptote is not yet determined.

A pre-registered falsifiability prediction states that under projected factor-5 improvement in $\sigma(m_t)$, the empirical power to distinguish $\mu = m_\tau$ from $\mu = \Sigma m_\ell$ as the crossing scale increases from $32\%$ to $81\%$, providing the principal opportunity to falsify the lepton-scale assignment. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or broader structural implication; the preference for $\mu = m_\tau$ is flagged as the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation.

