Combining the quark-mass contributions and $\alpha_s$ in quadrature gives a total input-propagation uncertainty of $\sigma_Q \approx 5.39 \times 10^{-4}$. The observed residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ is approximately a factor of ten smaller than this. This ratio is a \textit{measurement-precision} statement: the current uncertainty on $Q$ given published input masses and $\alpha_s$ is approximately ten times larger than the observed deviation from $2/3$, meaning that at current input precision the observed $Q$ value cannot be empirically distinguished from any value within a band of width $\sim \sigma_Q$ centered on $2/3$ (of which exact $2/3$ is one particular value, but so is $2/3 + 3 \times 10^{-4}$ and many others). This is not a statistical significance claim and should not be read as one; a frequentist characterization of how unusual this closure is requires a defined null distribution, which we construct in Section~\ref{sec:stats}.

Two features of the budget are worth noting. First, $m_t$ dominates---the PDG uncertainty on the top quark contributes more than 86\% of the quark-mass variance on $Q$. This is somewhat counterintuitive, since the scale scan varies $m_c$, not $m_t$; the point is that uncertainty propagation and sensitivity to the evaluation prescription are distinct quantities, and the Koide combination happens to weight the three masses in a way that makes $m_t

