The severity result is the most consequential numerical finding in this section. At current precision, the data have only $32\%$ power to reject $\mu^* = m_\tau$ in favor of $\mu^* = \Sigma m_\ell$: the two scales are not empirically distinguishable. At projected factor-5 precision on $m_t$, the power increases to $81\%$, and $m_\tau$ becomes empirically distinguishable from $\Sigma m_\ell$ at high confidence. \textit{This is the test the lepton-scale hypothesis will face in the next round of measurement updates.} The hypothesis predicts that as $\sigma(m_t)$ improves, the central value of the residual at $\mu = m_\tau$ will remain within the shrinking $\sigma_Q$ band; if the residual moves outside the band as inputs tighten, the hypothesis is excluded at the corresponding confidence level. The pre-registration of this prediction is documented in Section~\ref{sec:predictions}.

\paragraph{Visibility as a precision-era result.} The visibility of the closure relative to $\sigma_Q$ is itself a precision-era artifact in a substantive sense: under PDG 2010 uncertainties on $m_t$ (when $\sigma(m_t) \approx 1.4$~GeV, twice the current value), $\sigma_Q$ would have been approximately $1.0 \times 10^{-3}$ rather than the current $5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, and the residual-to-$\sigma$ ratio would have been at the $0.05$ level rather than the current $0.10$. The same observation, with the same algebra and the same scale prescription, would not have been visible as a structurally tight closure under input precision available a decade earlier. The result is therefore enabled by the precision of $m_t$ available in PDG 2024, and the same logic that makes future precision improvements informative (Prediction 1) also means that the closure's current visibility at $\sim 0.1\sigma$ is contingent on having precise measurements of all three input masses today.

\subsection{Discrete hypothesis scan and tiered analysis}
\label{sec:tiered}

The most stringent characterization of the observation is a discrete scan over the full enumerable hypothesis space defined by the construction in Section~\ref{sec:bounds}. Following a methodological recommendation grounded in the Higgs-search look-elsewhere framework \citep{GrossVitells2010,CousinsMayoHEP2020}, we performed a complete enumeration over four axes: (i) triple, with five candidates including same-generation sequential heavy and light triples and two mixed-generation alternatives; (ii) target fraction $p/q$ with $p, q$ positive integers, $q \leq 10$, restricted to the physically relevant range; (iii) evaluation scale, with fourteen candidates including all physical particle masses through the Higgs and several round-number reference scales (1, 1.5, 2, 3 GeV) included to populate the empirical noise floor; and (iv) sign pattern, with all four distinct sign assignments on the square roots after quotienting by the global sign-flip invariance of $Q$. The total grid contains $N = 10{,}640$ cells.

For each cell, we compute the approximate $\chi^2$ as $((Q_{\text{cell}} - Q_{\text{target}})/\sigma_Q)^2$ where $\sigma_Q$ is the propagated input uncertainty appropriate to that triple. Below-perturbative cells are flagged and excluded from the noise-floor analysis. Top cells are re-evaluated with the full profile-likelihood treatment for sharper numbers.

\paragraph{Tiered partition.} Following Cousins's principle that the look-elsewhere correction must reflect the trial structure that was actually employed, we partition the $N = 10{,}640$ cells into two tiers defined by the lepton-scale hypothesis as stated in the companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} \textit{prior to any heat-map computation}:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Tier~1}: cells for which the triple is $(c, b, t)$, the target is $Q = 2/3$ (Koide 1981), the scale is one of the two lepton-derived candidates ($m_\tau$ or $\Sigma m_\ell$), and the sign pattern is the standard Koide $(+,+,+)$. This is exactly two cells: \textbf{T1a} $= (c,b,t)$ at $(2/3, m_\tau)$ and \textbf{T1b} $= (c,b,t)$ at $(2/3, \Sigma m_\ell)$.
\item \textbf{Tier~2}: all $N_2 = 10{,}638$ remaining cells. These serve as the empirical noise floor and as a source of potential post-hoc discoveries for future investigation.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textit{Bright-line statement.} The tier partition was defined by the lepton-scale hypothesis from the companion note before the heat map computation; the assignment of cells to tiers does not depend on $\chi^2$ values or any other scan result. Tier~1 would have contained the same two cells regardless of where they ranked in the final $\chi^2$ ordering.

\paragraph{Tier~1 results.} The two pre-stated cells:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{T1a}: $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \, \mu = m_\tau, \, (+,+,+))$. $\chi^2 = 0.010$. The headline cell of the present paper. Empirical percentile against the Tier~2 noise floor: $0.011$th (1 of $9{,}118$ cells, Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI $[0.0003\%, 0.061\%]$).
\item \textbf{T1b}: $(c,b,t)$ at $(Q = 2/3, \, \mu = \Sigma m_\ell, \, (+,+,+))$. $\chi^2 = 2.15$. The other lepton-derived candidate from the discovery chronology. Empirical percentile against Tier~2: $0.16\%$ (15 of $9{,}118$ cells, 95\% CI $[0.092\%, 0.27\%]$). Rank 6 of the $2{,}280$ Tier~2 cells in the standard $(+,+,+)$ panel.
\end{itemize}
T1a is the closer fit; T1b is at the $\sim 1.5\sigma$ level. Both pre-stated cells sit in the upper tail of the empirical distribution. T1b is reported alongside T1a as a transparency element: the lepton-scale hypothesis tested two scales, only one produced a tight closure, and we report both outcomes as part of the pre-registered test.

The empirical percentile reported for T1a is the model-free frequency at which Tier~2 cells achieve $\chi^2$ as low as the pre-stated cell. We use the term \emph{percentile} rather than \emph{$p$-value} to make explicit that it is not the probability that the observation arises by chance under a generative model for the quark masses --- the Tier~2 distribution is not a generative model, it is the combinatorial noise floor of the discrete scan computed on the same measured masses. The percentile answers the question ``how unusual is the predicted cell's closure compared to the noise floor of the discrete scan?'' and not the question ``what is the probability that this observation arises by chance?''

\paragraph{Note on the Clopper-Pearson interval and cell correlations.} The Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI reported above treats the $9{,}118$ Tier~2 cells as independent binomial trials, which they strictly are not: $Q(\text{triple})(\mu)$ is a smooth function of $\mu$, and neighboring (target, scale) cells within the same triple and sign convention share most of their structural content. The effective sample size is therefore smaller than $9{,}118$ by a factor that we estimate but do not compute exactly here, conservatively bounded by the number of distinct (triple, sign) combinations ($5 \times 4 = 20$) times the number of independent scale clusters in the perturbative range (approximately $3$ when one accounts for the smooth $Q(\mu)$ correlation length), giving an effective sample size of $\sim 60$. The corrected Clopper-Pearson CI under that effective sample size is wider than the one reported, but the qualitative conclusion --- that T1a is at the lowest empirical $\chi^2$ percentile of the Tier~2 distribution and that no other cell in the scan with standard $(+,+,+)$ Koide signs survives fine-grid verification --- is robust to the correlation correction. A block-bootstrap correction that respects the smooth-curve structure within each (triple, sign) panel is left to future work.

\paragraph{Tier~2 noise-floor characterization.} The empirical CDF of $\chi^2$ across the $N_2 = 9{,}118$ Tier~2 cells (excluding $1{,}520$ below-perturbative sentinel cells) defines the noise-floor distribution. Of these cells:
\begin{itemize}
\item $8$ cells have $\chi^2 < 1$
\item $22$ cells have $\chi^2 < 4$
\item $39$ cells have $\chi^2 < 9$
\end{itemize}

