\subsection{Interpretation register}
\label{sec:stats_register}

The frequency statements in Sections~\ref{sec:null_mc}--\ref{sec:tiered} are model-conditional descriptive frequencies under explicitly defined Monte Carlo or scan constructions, not unconditional $p$-values against a physical null. The constructions condition on different things --- the Koide-conditioned null (Section~\ref{sec:null_mc}) conditions on the functional form and on the Koide-saturation of the prior over triples; the parametric bootstrap (Section~\ref{sec:bootstrap}) conditions on the observed input central values and the Gaussian model for measurement uncertainties; the tiered scan (Section~\ref{sec:tiered}) conditions on the discrete hypothesis space defined in Section~\ref{sec:bounds} and on the pre-stated Tier~1/Tier~2 partition. They answer different questions and they should not be combined into a single $p$-value: as Cousins emphasizes \citep{CousinsMayoHEP2020}, methods for combining $p$-values such as Fisher's, Stouffer's, or Lancaster's require that the individual $p$-values test the same null hypothesis, which these do not.

We therefore report the constructions side-by-side, with each null stated explicitly, and we do not attempt to derive a unified significance metric. The reader who wants a single number is directed to the profile likelihood scan of Section~\ref{sec:confdist} as the primary inferential object, from which any specific consistency statement at any chosen confidence level can be read off directly. The other constructions provide complementary characterizations under different conditioning, useful for bounding the surprise across a range of reasonable null assumptions.

\section{Bounds on the Search Space}
\label{sec:bounds}

Before disclosing the chronology of the observation, we make explicit the structural bounds on the search space within which the observation was located. Standard look-elsewhere corrections assume a search over a continuous parameter manifold in which the author has freedom to vary the functional form of the relation, the objects entering it, and the quantitative coefficients. None of those freedoms was exercised in the present work. We state the bounds here, before the chronology in Section~\ref{sec:chronology}, so that the chronology can be read as a complete enumeration of discrete trials within a fixed construction rather than as a partial disclosure of an open-ended scan.

\paragraph{The algebraic form is fixed.} The relation under test is Koide's $Q = 2/3$, published in 1981 \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}, with all coefficients and exponents held at their published values. We did not tune the coefficient $2/3$. We did not test variants with different symmetric polynomials in $m_i$ and $\sqrt{m_i}$, with different normalizations, or with alternative weightings across the three masses. We did not consider Koide-like families parameterized by a free exponent. The form was fixed before the observation and is fixed in the final result. The companion-note geometric reading \citep{Kocik2012,BrilliantStrange2026} is likewise inherited from prior literature and not varied here.

\paragraph{The choice of a three-particle form rather than a four-particle Soddy extension was deliberate and constraining.} The Koide $Q = 2/3$ relation is a single algebraic constraint over three masses. The Descartes/Soddy circle theorem over four curvatures, which appears in the companion note on the lepton-Descartes side, has an additional degree of freedom (the fourth curvature) and more parameter space in which to accommodate a match. We deliberately started from the three-particle Koide form rather than the four-particle Descartes form for the quark-sector test, because the three-particle form has fewer degrees of freedom and a closure in the more constrained form is structurally stronger than a closure in the less constrained form. A sanity probe of four-particle Soddy extensions in the quark sector was performed \textit{after} the present Koide observation was in hand; it is not part of the discovery search reported here and its results are deferred to future work.

\paragraph{The remaining degrees of freedom are discrete and enumerable.} Within a fixed Koide-$Q = 2/3$ form, the only remaining choices are: (i) which three particles enter the triple, and (ii) at what renormalization scale each mass is evaluated. The candidate triples at mass scales where a Koide-type closure has any numerical hope are bounded by physics: mass-ordered heavy-quark triples in the perturbative regime consist of a small number of natural choices, of which $(c, b, t)$ is the next-step extension of Rivero's 2011 $(s, c, b)$ construction \citep{Rivero2011}. The candidate scales for each mass are similarly bounded: self-scales, neighboring quark masses, lepton masses, conventional reference scales ($2$~GeV), and perturbative-regime lepton-derived quantities ($\sum m_\ell$). The full set of ``natural'' candidates across both dimensions is of order ten, not of order $10^3$ or higher. The search space is not a continuous manifold; it is an enumerable discrete set.

\paragraph{The author did not scan algebraic or mathematical space; the author queried a precomputed table.} The computational operation performed during discovery was a lookup. A precomputed table of four-loop running quark masses at standard reference scales (available as \texttt{quark\_running\_lookup.json} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy}) was consulted with specific candidate $(triple, scale)$ pairs. Koide's $Q$ was then evaluated on each queried row. This is a discrete operation over a finite table, not a scan over a continuous parameter space, and it can be audited by any reader who rebuilds the table from the published script. No algebraic machinery was invented during discovery; no new combinations were constructed from Koide's form; no tuning was performed on the coefficient or the exponents. The operation was: pick a triple, pick scales, read the table, compute $Q$.

\paragraph{What the bounds do and do not imply for multiplicity.} We do not claim that these structural bounds reduce the effective multiplicity to unity. The chronology in Section~\ref{sec:chronology} discloses that two explicit scale trials were performed before the observation was in hand, and a reader applying a correction factor of order two to the observed residual is applying a correct correction within the discrete search reported. What the bounds establish is that the correction factor is small and finite, that the search was not over a continuous manifold of possible relations, and that the relevant trial count is auditable from the repository and the chronology together. The look-elsewhere correction appropriate to this paper is of order the discrete trial count disclosed in Section~\ref{sec:chronology}, not of order the combinatorial size of all symmetric polynomials one could write down in six quark masses.

\section{Order of Operations and Prior-Knowledge Disclosure}
\label{sec:chronology}

Having bounded the search space to a small enumerable discrete set in Section~\ref{sec:bounds}, we now disclose the chronology by which elements of that set were actually tested during discovery. This is the complete list of explicit trials performed before the observation was in hand.

\paragraph{Chronology.} The observation was arrived at in the following sequence, starting from the companion note's strange-mass result \citep{BrilliantStrange2026}.
\begin{enumerate}
\item After the companion note's observation that a lepton-derived scale ($\Sigma m_\ell$) produces a numerical match for $m_s$, the author adopted the working hypothesis that lepton-derived scales might serve as natural evaluation scales for other Koide-type closures, with the aim of distinguishing a single numerical coincidence in one sector from a pattern across sectors.
\item The test target was selected as the heavy triple $(c, b, t)$, on the basis that it is the minimal next-step extension of Rivero's 2011 $(s, c, b)$ construction \citep{Rivero2011} under the lepton-scale modification. No search was performed over alternative heavy-quark triples before this choice.
\item Within $(c, b, t)$, only $m_c$ was treated as the candidate for rescaling, because $m_t$ is conventionally defined at its pole or self-scale and cannot plausibly be run to a lepton scale, and $m_b$ at $m_b(m_b) \approx 4.2$~GeV cannot be moved to a lepton scale without a fractional shift of order unity, which would be numerically implausible to preserve any tight relation.
\item The first scale tested for $m_c$ was $\Sigma m_\ell$, the scale carried over from the companion note. At this scale, the residual was $+7.47 \times 10^{-4}$: tighter than all quark-derived alternatives, but not at the level of the companion note's strange observation. The residual was positive, indicating that a slightly lighter scale would reduce it.
\item The second scale tested was $m_\tau$, which is the heaviest individual charged lepton and sits approximately $106$~MeV below $\Sigma m_\ell$. At this scale the residual was $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$, the result reported in this paper.
\end{enumerate}

The explicit number of scale trials performed during discovery was therefore \textit{two}. No additional scales or alternative triples were tested prior to this result. The post-discovery scan reported in Table~\ref{tab:alt_scales} was performed after the $m_\tau$ hit, for the purpose of characterizing the local scale landscape; it is not part of the discovery search.

\paragraph{Disclosure of prior knowledge.} The disclosure above gives the count of explicit trials during discovery, but this count does not capture the full implicit search, because the candidate set was bounded by prior internalized knowledge of the quark running-mass landscape. In the six weeks preceding this observation, the author assembled a precomputed lookup table of four-loop running quark masses at standard reference scales (available as \texttt{quark\_running\_lookup.json} in the accompanying repository \citep{RepoHeavy}), originally for unrelated work. By the time of the present observation, the author was sufficiently familiar with the contents of this table that candidate scales which would obviously fail---scales in the non-perturbative regime ($m_e, m_\mu$), scales at which the required running of $m_c$ would be of order unity in fractional shift (e.g., $m_t$ as a charm scale), and non-lepton-derived reference scales outside the $1$--$2$~GeV band---were eliminated from explicit consideration before any computation was performed. The two scales explicitly tested ($\Sigma m_\ell$ and $m_\tau$) were the two perturbative-regime lepton-derived candidates remaining after this implicit filtering.

This silent narrowing is a form of search that is not captured by the explicit trial count. A reader applying look-elsewhere corrections over the full space of scales the author could in principle have tested, rather than the two that were explicitly tested, should do so at their own discretion; we flag the existence of the implicit filtering here rather than pretending the search was uniform. The cheat sheet itself is a discrete lookup artifact, not a continuous search space, and is auditable from the repository: the full set of running values consulted during discovery is the same set available to any reader who rebuilds the table from the published script.

\paragraph{Intentional conservation of the search budget.} After the $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ observation, the author deliberately did not extend the search to adjacent heavy-quark triples or to alternative evaluation scale rules within the same triple. This decision was made to avoid inflating the effective trial count across the research program and to preserve each observation as an independent hypothesis test rather than as a fit to a scan. Future work may extend the search to additional triples---and such extension may strengthen or weaken the lepton-scale hypothesis depending on outcomes---in which case the multiplicity will be accounted for in that future work's statistical treatment. The present paper reports the outcome of a single hypothesis test, not a scan; the trial count disclosed above is complete for this paper.

\section{Caveats and Non-Claims}
\label{sec:caveats}

We make the following non-claims explicit.

\paragraph{Not a derivation.} We have not derived $Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework. The observation is post-hoc in the sense that $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t(m_t)$ were all established measurements at the time the scan was performed.

\paragraph{Not a prediction.} The relation was not written down in advance of any quark-mass measurement and then confirmed; the masses involved were already established.

\paragraph{Not a derivation of $\mu = m_\tau$.} We do not derive the preference for $m_\tau$ as the charm evaluation scale. The motivating heuristic---that $m_\tau$ is the heaviest charged lepton and sits in the 1-2~GeV window where a lepton-derived scale could plausibly match the charm sector---is offered as the reason $m_\tau$ was tested, not as an explanation of why it is the sharpest of the candidates. Why $m_\tau$ specifically, rather than any other scale in the $1$-$2$~GeV range, is the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation and we make no attempt to answer it here.

\paragraph{Not a mechanism.} We do not propose a flavor-symmetry mechanism, a matching condition, a grand-unified embedding, or any other structural reason that would generate $Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders.

\paragraph{Not the only quark-sector Koide relation, and not a universal claim about them.} Rivero \citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to $\approx 2\%$ in 2011 and developed the chained-Koide ``waterfall'' construction. The present $(c, b, t)$ observation is one generation up from Rivero's construction. We have not tested the $(s, c, b)$ triple under any lepton-scale hypothesis in this paper, and we do not make any prediction about that triple here. The present paper reports a single observation on a single triple and explicitly does not claim that lepton-derived scales produce tight Koide closures universally across quark-sector Koide-type relations. Such a universal claim would require a theoretical framework mapping lepton scales to specific quark triples, which is not developed here and is outside the scope of this paper. The relation between the present observation and Rivero's $(s, c, b)$ construction---whether they are fragments of a common underlying structure, or independent observations---is an open question that is deliberately not addressed here. A post-discovery sanity probe of four-particle Soddy/Descartes extensions in the quark sector was also performed (noted in Section~\ref{sec:bounds}); it is not part of the present paper's scope and its characterization is deferred to future work.

\paragraph{Not a scheme-invariant relation.} The closure is specific to the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme with the charm evaluation scale $\mu = m_\tau$. Converting the three masses to a uniform pole-mass treatment would shift $m_t$ by $\approx 10$~GeV relative to its $\overline{\text{MS}}$ self-scale value, which would dominate and destroy the observed closure. The present observation is consistent with the interpretation that it picks out a specific scheme-and-scale combination, not a scheme-independent identity, and we present it as such.

\paragraph{Not independent of the companion note.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a lepton-derived quantity matching $m_s$ at a lepton-derived scale. The present paper reports a quark-internal relation at a lepton-derived scale ($m_\tau$). Both observations involve lepton masses entering the characterization of a quark-sector quantity, and it is plausible that they are two facets of a common structural relation. We do not develop this possibility here.

\paragraph{Not a significance claim from measurement precision.} The ratio of the observed residual $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ to the propagated input uncertainty $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ is a measurement-precision metric, not a significance metric. We report it only to characterize the current resolution with which $Q$ is known given input quark masses and $\alpha_s$. A proper frequentist significance characterization against a defined null distribution is carried out separately in Section~\ref{sec:stats}, via null-model Monte Carlo (under several priors), profile likelihood ratio test with Wilks calibration, and parametric bootstrap with look-elsewhere correction. The results of those tests, not the measurement-precision ratio, are the appropriate basis for assessing how unusual the observation is under any specific null hypothesis.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Relation to the companion note.} The companion note \citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported that the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple matches $m_s^{\overline{\text{MS}}}$ at $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. The present paper reports that the Koide relation over the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ closes to well within input uncertainty when $m_c$ is evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$. The two observations share the feature that a lepton-sector scale---$\Sigma m_\ell \approx 1883$~MeV in the first case, $m_\tau = 1777$~MeV in the second---enters the characterization of a quark-sector quantity. In both cases, the lepton-derived scale produces a closure that is substantially tighter than neighboring natural alternatives. The two scales differ by $\approx 106$~MeV in $\mu$ and are not equivalent; whether their proximity is incidental or structural is not something we resolve at current precision.

\paragraph{Note on independence.} The two papers share the lepton-scale hypothesis as a common motivating idea but the empirical observations are independent: the companion note used a Soddy-Descartes geometric construction over lepton masses to predict $m_s$, while the present paper uses Koide's algebraic form on a different triple ($(c, b, t)$ rather than the leptons), with different quark masses, a different mathematical operation, and a different target scale. The masses involved in the two papers are disjoint (one uses lepton masses to predict a quark mass, the other uses quark masses to test a Koide closure), the formulas are different (Soddy curvature vs. Koide $Q$), and the predictions are different (a single mass value vs. a closure to a rational target). The shared element is the hypothesis that lepton-derived scales enter the characterization of quark-sector quantities, and the two papers test it on independent empirical objects. We therefore treat them as two empirical instances of the same minimal hypothesis, not as circular validation of a single observation: the test in the present paper would have failed (and the paper would not exist) if $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu = m_\tau}$ had not closed, regardless of the result of the companion note.

\paragraph{Relation to Rivero's (s, c, b) construction.} Rivero's 2011 note \citep{Rivero2011} reported a Koide-type closure for the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ at approximately the $2\%$ level, and developed the chained-``waterfall'' construction. The present observation is structurally different from Rivero's in three respects. First, it concerns a different triple: $(c, b, t)$ rather than $(s, c, b)$. Second, it uses all three square roots with positive sign (no $-\sqrt{}$ convention). Third, it uses a specific renormalization scale for the charm quark ($\mu = m_\tau$) that is not the charm self-scale and is not otherwise motivated in the quark-sector literature we are aware of. The tightness of the present closure ($\approx 10^{-4}$ relative, within input uncertainty) is approximately two orders of magnitude better than Rivero's, and the character of the observation is different: Rivero's is a single-scale algebraic near-closure, the present one is a scale-dependent closure that is only tight at a specific prescription.

\paragraph{The principal open question.} Why $\mu = m_\tau$? The observation is sharp in scale among lepton-derived candidates: the alternative lepton scale $\Sigma m_\ell$ produces a residual approximately fifteen times larger, and the quark self-scales produce residuals two to three orders of magnitude larger. Within the standard Koide $(+,+,+)$ sign convention, the discrete enumeration of Section~\ref{sec:tiered} finds that the predicted Tier~1 cell at $(c,b,t)$, $Q = 2/3$, $\mu = m_\tau$ is the only cell hitting all three structural conditions of the lepton-scale hypothesis simultaneously. The window in $\mu$ around $m_\tau$ within which $|Q - 2/3|$ remains below the input-propagated $\sigma_Q$ is approximately $140$~MeV wide (about $4\%$ of $m_\tau$ itself), and the value of $Q$ at $m_\tau$ is not currently empirically distinguishable from exact $2/3$. The severity analysis in Section~\ref{sec:severity} quantifies what the current data can and cannot distinguish, and what would become distinguishable at projected future precision. Any eventual explanation of the observation must account for the specific preference for $m_\tau$ as the charm evaluation scale, not merely for ``some scale in the $1$-$2$~GeV range.''~We offer no such explanation and make no conjecture.

\paragraph{Predictions and falsifiability.} The observation as reported is post-hoc in the sense that all three input masses were established measurements at the time of discovery. To convert it from a post-hoc regularity into a falsifiable scientific claim, we have archived two pre-registered predictions in the accompanying repository (\texttt{predictions\_preregistered.md}, committed at the reproducibility hash cited in Section~\ref{sec:computational}).

\textit{Prediction 1: Robustness under improving input precision.} Current $\sigma(m_t) = 0.7$~GeV dominates the measurement-precision budget on $Q$. Projected future precision under a factor-5 reduction in $\sigma(m_t)$ (corresponding approximately to an HL-LHC scenario) reduces $\sigma_Q$ from $5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ to $\approx 1.6 \times 10^{-4}$, and the empirical power to distinguish $\mu = m_\tau$ from $\mu = \Sigma m_\ell$ as the crossing scale increases from $32\%$ to $81\%$ (Section~\ref{sec:severity}). The prediction is: if the relation $Q|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$ is exact or approximately exact, the central value of the residual should remain within the reduced $\sigma_Q$ as input precision improves. If the central value drifts outside the reduced $\sigma_Q$, the exact-closure interpretation is excluded at the corresponding confidence level. This is a genuine forward prediction that can be tested without additional work by the author once FLAG/PDG updates are published. Equivalently, the Feldman-Cousins interval on $\mu^*$ (Section~\ref{sec:fc_crossing}) will shrink under improved precision, and the prediction is that the shrinking interval continues to contain $m_\tau$ at $1\sigma$.

\textit{Prediction 2: Five-loop QCD running and asymptotic behavior.} The perturbative loop-order progression of the residual at $\mu = m_\tau$ is monotone in sign:
\begin{itemize}
\item 1-loop: residual $-2.07 \times 10^{-3}$
\item 2-loop: residual $-5.09 \times 10^{-4}$
\item 3-loop: residual $-8.79 \times 10^{-5}$
\item 4-loop: residual $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ \quad \textit{(reference value used in this paper)}
\item 5-loop: residual $+8.37 \times 10^{-5}$ \quad \textit{(computed in the accompanying repository, see archived predictions)}
\end{itemize}
The 4-loop and 5-loop residuals are both within $\sigma_Q = 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ of zero, individually consistent with exact closure. However, the same-sign progression at 4-loop and 5-loop, combined with the residual not yet decreasing toward zero, means the all-orders asymptote of the perturbative series at $\mu = m_\tau$ is not yet determined. Two scientifically distinct possibilities remain consistent with the data:
\begin{description}
\item[(A)] $Q$ converges to exactly $2/3$ as the loop order $\to \infty$, and the $\sim 5$-$8 \times 10^{-5}$ residuals at 4-loop and 5-loop are perturbative truncation artifacts that vanish at higher orders.
\item[(B)] $Q$ converges to a value within $\sim 10^{-4}$ of $2/3$ but not exactly, and the residual at sufficiently high loop order asymptotes to a small but non-zero value indistinguishable from exact at current measurement precision.
\end{description}
At current input precision, $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ is approximately five times larger than the difference between (A) and (B), so the data cannot distinguish them. The prediction is: as future input precision improves to the projected $\sigma_Q \approx 1.6 \times 10^{-4}$, the difference between (A) and (B) becomes empirically resolvable at approximately the $1\sigma$ level. Combined with eventual 6-loop or 7-loop computations, the asymptotic value of the perturbative series will become measurable, and the choice between (A) and (B) becomes a forward, testable statement. We do not commit to either possibility at present.

Each prediction is a severe test in the sense of Mayo and Spanos: a test the observation could fail. An observation that survives multiple severe tests earns credence; an observation that has only passed the test that discovered it has not been tested at all. Neither prediction depends on any theoretical framework beyond existing perturbative QCD and measurement infrastructure, and both are archived at a specific commit hash so the predictions cannot be retrospectively adjusted to match eventual outcomes.

\paragraph{Conclusions.} We have reported that the Koide relation $Q = 2/3$ holds for the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ with a residual of $+5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ when $m_c$ is evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme, with $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their self-scales, computed at four-loop QCD via \texttt{CRunDec}. The residual is approximately a factor of ten smaller than the propagated input-uncertainty budget $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated by the PDG uncertainty on $m_t$: at current measurement precision, the observed $Q$ is indistinguishable from any value in a band of width $\sim \sigma_Q$ around $2/3$. The zero-crossing of $(Q - 2/3)$ on the continuous scale scan lies $7.3$~MeV below $m_\tau$, and $m_\tau$ is likewise indistinguishable from the crossing scale at current precision on the $\mu$ axis. These are measurement-precision statements.

The full frequentist characterization of Section~\ref{sec:stats} reports a profile likelihood scan (the primary inferential object) consistent with $\Delta Q = 0$ at $1\sigma$, a profile likelihood ratio test that is degenerate at current input precision (Wilks's theorem fails by approximately two orders of magnitude due to the four nuisance parameters absorbing the constraint at near-zero cost), a Koide-conditioned null-model Monte Carlo placing the observation at the $\sim 0.4$ percentile of the null under four priors, a parametric bootstrap returning $\sim 7\%$ local and $\sim 42\%$ global $p$-values (with effective trials factor $5.8$ over six natural scales), a Feldman-Cousins 68\% CL interval on the crossing scale that contains $m_\tau$ but not $\Sigma m_\ell$, and a severity result showing that the data have $32\%$ power at current precision but $81\%$ power at projected factor-5 $\sigma(m_t)$ to distinguish $\mu = m_\tau$ from $\mu = \Sigma m_\ell$. The discrete enumeration of Section~\ref{sec:tiered} partitions the $N = 10{,}640$ scan cells into a Tier~1 of cells pre-stated by the lepton-scale hypothesis (two cells) and a Tier~2 noise floor (the remaining $9{,}118$ non-flagged cells); the predicted Tier~1 cell at $(c,b,t)$, $Q = 2/3$, $\mu = m_\tau$ achieves $\chi^2 = 0.010$ and ranks at the $0.011$th percentile of the Tier~2 noise floor (1 of $9{,}118$ cells, Clopper-Pearson 95\% CI $[0.0003\%, 0.061\%]$). After fine-grid verification applied uniformly to all eight sub-$\chi^2 = 1$ cells across all four sign panels, the predicted cell is the unique cell in the entire scan whose $\chi^2$ is irreducible at a hypothesis-stated or named scale; every other sub-$1$ cell, regardless of sign convention, is verified as a discretization artifact with reduction factors between $73\times$ and $\sim 10^5\times$ under fine-grid resampling. Rivero's 2011 $(s,c,b)$ observation is recovered as a $\sim 1.5\sigma$ warm spot under the $-\sqrt{m_s}$ sign convention, providing a cross-check on the scan infrastructure. We do not combine these characterizations into a unified significance metric; each conditions on different things and answers a different question, and the profile likelihood scan is the appropriate object from which any specific consistency statement can be read off.

The discovery procedure consisted of two explicit scale trials, within an implicit search bounded by prior familiarity with the running-mass landscape. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or broader structural implication. The preference for $\mu = m_\tau$ is flagged as the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation. Two pre-registered predictions---robustness under improving $m_t$ precision, and the asymptotic behavior of the perturbative series including the now-computed 5-loop residual---are archived in the accompanying repository to support falsification as future measurements and calculations become available.

\section*{Computational Note}
\label{sec:computational}

Central values, four-loop running, Koide-closure evaluations, input-uncertainty propagation, scale scans, and the natural-scale comparison table are reproducible from the accompanying GitHub repository \citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec} \citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.2807$~GeV, $m_b(m_b) = 4.203$~GeV, and $m_t(m_t) = 162.5$~GeV. The precomputed quark running lookup table (\texttt{quark\_running\_lookup.json}, generated by \texttt{build\_lookup.py}) contains 1022 logarithmically-spaced scale points from 1~GeV to 10~TeV with full threshold matching, and was the object of the order-of-operations disclosure in Section~\ref{sec:chronology}. The scale-comparison table of Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales} is produced by \texttt{heavy\_koide\_scale\_table.py}.

The statistical characterization of Section~\ref{sec:stats} is implemented as a set of independent Python scripts: \texttt{heavy\_koide\_null.py} (Section~\ref{sec:null_mc}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_plr.py} (Section~\ref{sec:plr}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_bootstrap.py} (Section~\ref{sec:bootstrap}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_fc\_crossing.py} (Section~\ref{sec:fc_crossing}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_severity.py} (Section~\ref{sec:severity}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_confdist.py} (Section~\ref{sec:confdist}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_landscape\_2d.py} and \texttt{heavy\_koide\_selectivity\_scan.py} and \texttt{heavy\_koide\_fisher.py} and \texttt{heavy\_koide\_single\_mass\_sensitivity.py} (the landscape analysis underlying Section~\ref{sec:tiered}), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_heatmap.py} and \texttt{heavy\_koide\_empirical\_null.py} (the full $10{,}640$-cell scan and empirical-null analysis), \texttt{heavy\_koide\_tiered\_analysis.py} (the tiered partition with empirical $p$-values), and \texttt{heavy\_koide\_grid\_artifact\_check.py} (the fine-grid verification of Tier~2 cells). All output JSON files (\texttt{heavy\_koide\_null.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_plr.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_bootstrap.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_fc\_crossing.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_severity.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_confdist.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_landscape.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_heatmap.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_tiered.json}, \texttt{heavy\_koide\_grid\_artifact.json}) are archived at the cited commit hash, along with the figures referenced in Section~\ref{sec:stats}. All input values are PDG 2024 \citep{PDG2024} and FLAG 2024 \citep{FLAG2024} central values at the time of computation; the repository archives exact input values and the \texttt{CRunDec} version used. The pre-registered predictions of Section~\ref{sec:discussion} are archived as \texttt{predictions\_preregistered.md} at the same commit. Total runtime for the full analysis is approximately twenty minutes on a laptop; the dominant cost is the discrete heat map scan ($\sim 15$~minutes for $10{,}640$ cells with full input running).

